    Customer Reviews, including Product Star Ratings help customers to learn more about the product and decide whether it is the right product for them.

    To calculate the overall star rating and percentage breakdown by star, we dont use a simple average. Instead, our system considers things like how recent a review is and if the reviewer bought the item on Amazon. It also analyzed reviews to verify trustworthiness.

    My opinions on pros and cons:
    PROS:
    - BEAUTIFUL screen.. I havent used a recent iphone display, but I imagine iphones displays are very nice as well. I do own the 12.9 m1 ipad with the miniLED display and I would much rather have a screen like this S22U on my ipad. IMO, my Samsung Tab S7+ DISPLAY is better than my 12.9 M1 miniLED display. The BLOOM that occurs with miniLED destroys any sort of immersion and is beyond distracting with certain visuals. Dont get me wrong, the miniLED is beautiful as well.. As long as youre looking at content that doesnt accentuate the very obvious shortcomings of miniLED. OLED>miniLED. So if you own any of those, youll be happy with the S22U display for sure.
    - I LOVE the touch protection feature.. Love it on my Tab S7+ too allowing the screen to go to 0 percent brightness after a set specific amount of time.. So the device doesnt actually turn off/lock the phone.. Just lowers the brightness to save battery and w/e. I play some games where it has to do an action for a while and I just sorta have to sit there until its done, this allows the phone to save battery by turning the brightness down to 0%. Also being able to set different brightness levels for this setting.. Such an awesome feature.
    - Everything Ive used the S22U with has been very snappy.. Any issues Ive had with apps are usually due to the devs poor coding. That's not to say that ONEui isn't the cause of some of the stuttering issues (i.g. camera shutter, etc)
    - spen.. You can do a lot with this. Just google or youtube it.
    - fairly good support and updates. Though, I still haven't gotten the android 13 update.. pretty annoying.
    - USB C.. feels silly to mention this, but since apple still uses their archaic lightning connector.. some consumers might think there aren't other options when it comes to connectors.
    - Minimal packaging.. This, imo, is a huge plus.. There isnt a need to waste resources and increase cost to consumers by creating an irrelevant unboxing experience. Samsung also uses recycled materials to make the box which is also great.
    - Samsungs OS is actually very nice. Very feature filled with actually useful features. I would like to see settings be more intuitively organized. But the search feature in the settings can alleviate this issue.
    - The matte black finish on the back of this phone is chef's kiss.
    - DEX is very useful, however I wish one could use DEX on the S22U as standalone oppose to having to connect it to an external monitor or source.
    CONS:
    *VERY IMPORTANT CON* Samsung needs to fire the person who thumbs upped the go ahead to use curved edges. There is a reason no one else uses curved edges. No one likes them. And the people who do like them are so small that samsung is driving away people who would otherwise buy their phone if it didnt have curved edges. stop using curved edgesonyourdisplay
    - CONSTANT issues with false touches on the screen due to the curved edges. Also, sometimes when Im trying to press something or type.. It wont register can you guess why? Its because of the curved edges.. My other fingers or palms are touching the curved edges (while holding the phone normally) which are not allowing my actual fingers to type or play a game. I assumed samsung would have this 100% under control and figured out if theyre putting it in a $1,200 phone.. But I guess they 100% do not. Its honestly a dealbreaker and I would return this phone due to the screen being so unreliable if I didnt need/want the pen functionality of this phone. My hands/fingers are pretty scrawny.. So if your hands and fingers are a bit thiccer.. Youre going to 100% have issues. That said, if youre planning on using a case, this could prevent these issues some-what. (good luck finding a good case that properly protects the curved edges.. every case I've seen for this phone either doesn't have protection for the curved edges or it's so minimal that it doesn't do anything.) I was planning to use my phone w/o a case, but now I will 100% have to use a phone case to try and alleviate some of the false touches a curved display causes. If the S23U or any future samsung phone uses a curved display.. I will 100% not even consider it to be a prospective purchase.
    - most if not all screen protectors and cases dont actually protect the screen properly due to the curved edge display. If you look closely.. The curved edges on the S22U will still be exposed on 99% of the phone cases for the S22U. Same with screen protectors.. They either dont work properly due to the curved edge display, or they just dont even bother trying to cover the curved edge display. Why? Because curved edge displays are impractical and dont even look good. It's not really the fault of the case makers.. it's samsungs fault for use a crappy curved edge display.. if case makers made the side lips more snug or "raised higher" it will interfere with the curved part of the display which would make touches/gestures impossible to achieve. So again.. it's almost impossible to make a good case for curved edge displays whilst still making them 'minimalistic.'
    *at this point youre probably thinking.. These are all just issues with the curved edge display*
    You would be correct.. The curved edge display is so terrible it causes so many more issues than just being a terrible display choice. Again, I want to stress that the actual visual quality of the display is FANTASTIC.. but the functionality of the curved edge display is HORRIFIC. It's actually so sad.. because if samsung just made a NORMAL edged display with the s22u.. it would be such an amazingly no-compromise phone (at least when it comes with the display)
    - the camera *area* redesign is ugly and less protective than the last gen. this is obviously my opinion. I know many ppl, for some reason, think this looks good. The S21U had a nice flush area that actually looks good with the rest of the phone and protected the lens casing or w/e its called. Now on the S22U each lens surrounding casings are exposed and there are actual physical areas between each of the lenses. This causes that area to easily collect dust and it just looks so awful. Again.. The person who designed this.. Wow.. do they still work for samsung? My god. Every time I set my phone on a flat surface.. I can literally hear the clank of the lenses hit that surface because they extrude from the phone's housing w/o any protection or w/e. It makes me wonder how many times I can set my phone on a table or w/e before the lenses start to crack due to the poor design choice of the lens area. NOW if youre planning to use a phone case.. This becomes less of an issue, obviously. And sure, you can buy quality compromising lens cover or w/e. Nah.. Im not going to do that because those are terrible for photo quality. Why would I pay $1200 and then use a $10 lens cover that will destroy the picture quality? Makes zero sense.
    - fingerprint reader just doesnt seem very fast. A $1200 phone should have an instant unlock fingerprint reader.
    - Speakers are plenty loud.. But 'LOUD' does not translate to good sound quality. The S22U doesnt have BAD sound.. Its just average tho. For $1200.. Id expect the sound to be much better than it actually is.
    - phone wobbles very badly (when flat on its back) due to the poor camera design. This is a big issue since.. Well.. youre probably going to be using the spen a lot. And I do try to use it on the table a lot. Obviously youll be using the spen while holding the phone, too.. But guess what.. Due to the curved edge display.. Youre going to be running into a lot of false touches and even unresponsiveness due to your hand touching the curved edge display whilst you hold the phone and use the spen at the same time.
    - Gets alarmingly HOT. not warm.. It getS HOT.. if it were the summer.. Holding this phone while playing a game would causing my hands to perspire to the point where I would be worried about causing water damage to the internals of this phone even tho its water resistant. (on the other hand, its nice for the winter because it dont need to wear gloves because this thing keeps my hands toasty) One thing Ill always say is that its a good thing that you can feel the heat dissipating, because that means the internal heat pipes or heat sinks or vape chambers are doing their jobs and dissipating the heat from the cpu/mem/etc. That said, excessive heat will cause the internal hardware to wear down faster and/or cause hardware failure. So its a balancing act that I dont know too much about. One concerning thing about using this in the winter is that if something is very cold.. And gets very hot.. That might cause something to crack or break? No? I dunno.. Well see.
    And sure, you can turn down settings, go down to 720p for the display and 60hz, play games on low, ultra low, blah blah blah then why even pay for a flagship phone, ya? I've also tweaked settings in the Game Booster and CPU optimizer settings depending on what I'm doing. Still gets very hot.
    - not all models have 12GB of ram.. This is just greed tbh.
    - no sdcard slot. Go back to your roots, samsung. You dont have to chase apple, around the playground during recess, trying to be like them.
    - extremely slow charging* this is because all that is included with the $1200 purchase is a very short usb c cable. Wheres the charger? Huh? Gotta pad those profit margins? Well now I have a phone that takes 6 hours to charge because samsung didnt want to include a fast charger with their $1200 phone. Huh. ok. seems fair!
    - doesnt come with an outlet plug/adapter w/e you wanna call them. Again.. Must be greed. STOPEXCLUDINGTHECHARGINGADAPTERS You dont have to be that annoying kid on the playground that is constantly just copying all the cooler kids (arguably cool kids) who are now excluding something that 100% should be included with a $1200 purchase.
    If the logic of samsung's excuse to not include a charger is to help the earth/environment then that's just a lie.. because now people need to go out of their way to purchase a wall charger on their own.. and this might take a few purchases to find one that's actually good.. so now you have consumers purchasing multiple more products which means more waste and more deliveries. And the companies that are selling these phone charging adapters might not be trying to lower their footprint. All samsung has done is lowered THEIR green footprint (but not really.. they're just saying that) but has actually increased the footprint of other companies by 2-5 times? i duno.. now I have to go out of my way to find a wall charger. and of course I'm going to start out with more value oriented ones because the $1200 samsung phone doesn't include one in the box.. if they turn out to be a bust.. now I have to buy another whereas if samsung had just included one with their $1200 phone, we'd be gucci. so again, if the excuse is that they're lowering their footprint by not including a wall charger.. that logic is completely illogical.
    I wanted to get this phone due to it having a usable pen built into the body. for me, this is a very useful utility and the reason I purchased the S22U. Im wondering whether I should have went with the pixel 7 or waited for the iphone with USB c, next year. The curved edge display makes the S22U almost unusable.
    This is a weird statement, but this is a good phone with terrible design choices and implementations. Curved edge displays should be banned.

    + Great battery: much better than my old phone, I could carry this phone all day and not need to charge it until I'm home. I use it decently to watch YouTube, and by the time I'm done with my 8 hour shift, I still have 60% when I head home.
    + The S Pen was again my favorite feature from my last phone. They improved the battery life of it and also made more features with the pen! With motion swipes of the pen, you could zoom in and out of the camera and then take a photo. Along with that, also adjust music volume or just switch to the next song!

    Cons:
    - If you prefer to use the aux cord, Sadly they removed it from the phone. It sucks since not everything I own has adopted to bluetooth.
    - No SD card slot, which means if you want more storage, you can not upgrade or purchase an SD card. The only solution is to get a cloud storage or get the same phone but with more storage space.

    Overall, despite the few cons, I am happy with my purchase. I would be even happier if they didn't remove them, but I still enjoy it and I haven't encountered any problems after months of use.
